My meme

I re-created the inspo meme with the following key components and changes:
  1. First Cat Meme (img1):
    • Loaded and scaled the first cat meme (inspo_meme.jpg) to a width of 300 pixels using image_scale.
  2. First Square with Text (img1_text):
    • Created a black square with a text annotation (Ohno!) at the center using image_blank and image_annotate.
  3. Second Cat Meme (img2):
    • Loaded and scaled the second cat meme (inspo_meme1.jpeg) to a width of 300 pixels using image_scale.
  4. Second Square with Text (img2_text):
    • Created a black square with a text annotation (emmmm) at the center using image_blank and image_annotate.
  5. Combining Rows:
    • Combined the first cat meme and its text annotation horizontally using image_append to create the top row (top_row).
    • Combined the second cat meme and its text annotation horizontally using image_append to create the bottom row (bottom_row).
  6. Combining Rows Vertically:
    • Combined the two rows vertically using image_append(stack = TRUE).
  7. Final Image Scaling:
    • Scaled the final composite image to a width of 800 pixels using image_scale(500). 
# load first cat meme
img1 <- image_read("inspo_meme.jpg") %>%
  image_scale(300)

# first square
img1_text <- image_blank(width = 300, 
                          height = 300, 
                          color = "#000000") %>%
  image_annotate(text = "Ohno!",
                 color = "#FFFFFF",
                 size = 80,
                 font = "Impact",
                 gravity = "center")

# load second cat meme
img2 <- image_read("inspo_meme1.jpeg") %>%
  image_scale(300)

# second square
img2_text <- image_blank(width = 300, 
                          height = 300, 
                          color = "#000000") %>%
  image_annotate(text = "emmmm",
                 color = "#FFFFFF",
                 size = 80,
                 font = "Impact",
                 gravity = "center")

# making each row
# first using the approach we used above
cat_vector <- c(img1, img1_text)
top_row <- image_append(cat_vector)

# second using a different approach
bottom_row <- image_append(c(img2, img2_text))

# making the whole thing!

# using another approach
final_meme <- c(top_row, bottom_row) %>%
  image_append(stack = TRUE) %>%
  image_scale(500)

I re-created the animated meme with the following key components and changes:
  1. Cat Meme (img1):
    • Loaded and scaled the original cat meme (inspo_meme.jpg) to a width of 300 pixels using image_scale.
  2. Animated Frames:
    • Created four different frames (img1_frame1, img1_frame2, img1_frame3, img1_frame4) by annotating the original meme with different texts.
    • Used image_annotate to add text to each frame.
    • Positioned the text at the bottom (gravity = "south") for each frame.
  3. Animation Creation:
    • Combined the frames into a vector (img1_frames).
    • Used image_animate to create an animated GIF (img1_animation) with a frame rate of 1 frame per second. 
# load meme gif
img1_frame1 <- img1 %>%
  image_annotate(text = "Ohno!",
                 color = "#FFFFFF",
                 size = 80,
                 font = "Impact",
                 gravity = "south")

img1_frame2 <- img1 %>%
  image_annotate(text = "No way!",
                 color = "#FFFFFF",
                 size = 80,
                 font = "Impact",
                 gravity = "south")

img1_frame3 <- img1 %>%
  image_annotate(text = "OMG!",
                 color = "#FFFFFF",
                 size = 80,
                 font = "Impact",
                 gravity = "south")

img1_frame4 <- img1 %>%
  image_annotate(text = "OHHHH",
                 color = "#FFFFFF",
                 size = 80,
                 font = "Impact",
                 gravity = "south")

# putting the fist meme frames in order using a vector
img1_frames <- c(img1_frame1, img1_frame2, img1_frame3, img1_frame4)

# creating an animation
img1_animation <- image_animate(img1_frames, fps = 1)
